Multimodal Longitudinal Mental-Health Dataset (Synthetic)

This dataset simulates a six-timepoint longitudinal mental-health study commonly seen in computational psychiatry, digital phenotyping, and clinical outcomes research.
It contains three coordinated data modalities:

Clinical outcome ratings

Passive sensor behavior data

EMA-style natural language clinical notes

This dataset is ideal for:

1. Longitudinal mixed-effects modeling

2. Multimodal fusion

3. Computational psychiatry modeling

4. NLP + LLM-assisted clinical analysis

5. Precision outcome forecasting

These modalities mirror real-world psychiatric research workflows used within
UChicago BSD Psychiatry, Lyons Lab Precision Analytics, and digital phenotyping studies.

1Ô∏è‚É£ clinical_longitudinal_data.csv

This is the primary clinical dataset, containing demographic information, treatment assignment, and outcome severity over time.

| Column              | Type          | Description                                                                                                                     |
| ------------------- | ------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **participant_id**  | integer       | Unique identifier for each participant (1‚Äì120). Matches across sensor + text modalities.                                        |
| **timepoint**       | integer       | Longitudinal assessment index (1‚Äì6). Represents sequential study visits (weekly/biweekly/monthly).                              |
| **treatment_group** | integer (0/1) | Study condition:<br>**0 = control**, **1 = high-intensity therapy**. Affects improvement trajectory.                            |
| **symptom_score**   | float         | Psychiatric symptom severity score (higher = worse). Baseline ‚âà N(22,6). Decreases over time with treatment √ó time interaction. |
| **age**             | float         | Age drawn from N(35,10). Used as demographic covariate.                                                                         |
| **gender**          | categorical   | Gender identity (Male, Female, Other). Encoded via `C(gender)` in statistical modeling.                                         |

‚úî Summary

This dataset provides the core variables for longitudinal mixed-effects modeling, treatment-effect estimation, and demographic adjustment.

2Ô∏è‚É£ sensor_longitudinal_data.csv

Simulated passive ‚Äúdigital phenotyping‚Äù signals collected via smartphone or wearable devices.

| Column                  | Type    | Description                                                                  |
| ----------------------- | ------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **participant_id**      | integer | Matches clinical data.                                                       |
| **timepoint**           | integer | Matches clinical timepoints.                                                 |
| **avg_steps**           | float   | Mean daily steps. Lower values correspond to higher symptom burden (‚â• 500).  |
| **sleep_hours**         | float   | Nightly sleep duration (3.5‚Äì10 hrs). Higher symptoms ‚Üí more irregular sleep. |
| **phone_usage_minutes** | float   | Daily smartphone usage (30‚Äì600 min). Higher symptoms ‚Üí increased usage.      |

‚úî Interpretation of Sensor Variables

avg_steps ‚Üí psychomotor activity
Reduced movement is a known marker of depression/anxiety.

sleep_hours ‚Üí circadian stability
Sleep disruption correlates strongly with mood disorders.

phone_usage_minutes ‚Üí avoidance/rumination
Digital phenotyping studies show increased screen time during distress.

3Ô∏è‚É£ text_notes_longitudinal_data.csv

EMA-style, qualitative clinical notes describing each participant‚Äôs subjective mood and engagement.

| Column             | Type    | Description                                                                |
| ------------------ | ------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **participant_id** | integer | Matches clinical + sensor datasets.                                        |
| **timepoint**      | integer | Longitudinal visit index.                                                  |
| **note_text**      | string  | Mood/behavior narrative generated from symptom severity + treatment group. |

‚úî Example Note

‚ÄúAt visit 3, the participant reports struggling with mood but noticing some better days, while engaging regularly with therapy exercises. Sleep and energy fluctuate.‚Äù

‚úî Text Usage

1. NLP analysis

2. Sentiment trends

3. LLM interpretation

4. Qualitative support for sensor & clinical trajectories

üìä Multimodal Relationships Designed Into the Dataset

This dataset encodes scientifically grounded relationships among modalities.

üî∑ Clinical ‚Üí Sensor Patterns

Higher psychiatric symptom severity leads to:

| Symptom Change | Sensor Behavior                                                         |
| -------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| ‚Üë symptoms     | **‚Üì avg_steps** (psychomotor slowing, low energy)                       |
| ‚Üë symptoms     | **‚Üì sleep_hours** (insomnia, rumination)                                |
| ‚Üë symptoms     | **‚Üë phone_usage_minutes** (avoidance, doom-scrolling, late-night usage) |


These are validated in digital phenotyping research.

üî∑ Clinical ‚Üí Text Patterns

Symptom-based mapping:

| Symptom Score | Mood Description                   |
| ------------- | ---------------------------------- |
| > 22          | ‚Äúvery overwhelmed and anxious‚Äù     |
| 18‚Äì22         | ‚Äústruggling with mood‚Äù             |
| 14‚Äì18         | ‚Äúsomewhat better and more hopeful‚Äù |
| < 14          | ‚Äúmuch more stable and engaged‚Äù     |


Treatment-based phrasing:

Treatment group (1): ‚Äúengaging regularly with therapy and exercises‚Äù

Control group (0): ‚Äúattending check-ins but not in high-intensity therapy‚Äù

üß† Scientific Rationale: Why Symptoms Affect Steps, Sleep, Phone Use

The dataset encodes known behavioral associations:

1. Symptoms ‚Üí ‚Üì Steps

eople with higher symptoms demonstrate:

Reduced energy

Psychomotor slowing

Lower motivation

Social withdrawal

Less physical activity

Step count is a validated digital biomarker for depression severity.

2. Symptoms ‚Üí ‚Üì Sleep Stability

Higher symptoms cause:

  -Hyperarousal

  -Rumination

  -Fragmented sleep

  -Irregular circadian rhythms

Participants show:

  -Lower average sleep

  -Higher variability

  -More awakenings

3. Symptoms ‚Üí ‚Üë Phone Use

Distress increases screen usage due to:

People experiencing distress often compensate via:

  -Avoidant scrolling

  -Social media use

  -Late-night phone use

  -Reinforcement-seek behavior

Digital phenotyping studies consistently show:

‚Üë depression ‚Üí ‚Üë screen time

‚Üë anxiety ‚Üí ‚Üë compulsive checking

‚Üì sleep ‚Üí ‚Üë nighttime phone use

This correlation is widely documented in digital phenotyping literature.

